---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MascotTip from '../../components/MascotTip.astro';
import AuthorByline from '../../components/AuthorByline.astro';
import EmailCapture from '../../components/EmailCapture.astro';
import FAQSection from '../../components/FAQSection.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How I Earn $3,500+/Year in Rewards Without Changing My Spending | ProofLabs"
  description="Tyler's complete breakdown: the exact cards, cashback portals, and savings accounts that generate $3,500+ in annual rewards. Real numbers, real spending."
>
  <article style="max-width: 48rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 8rem 0 4rem;">
    <h1 style="font-size: 3rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text); line-height: 1.1;">
      How I Earn $3,500+/Year in Rewards Without Changing My Spending
    </h1>

    <AuthorByline date="March 15, 2026" />

    <div style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
      
      <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text); margin: 2rem 0;">
        Most people earn $200-300 per year in credit card rewards. I earn $3,500+.
      </p>

      <p>
        The difference isn't spending more money or gaming some complicated points system. It's stacking multiple optimization layers so every dollar I already spend works harder.
      </p>

      <p>
        I'm going to show you exactly how, with real numbers from my actual spending.
      </p>

      <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fed7aa 100%); border: 2px solid var(--color-accent); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 2rem; margin: 3rem 0; box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);">
        <h3 style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text); margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          The Full Breakdown
        </h3>
        <table style="width: 100%; font-size: 0.9375rem;">
          <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #f59e0b;">
            <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Credit card rewards</strong></td>
            <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 700;">~$2,500/year</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #f59e0b;">
            <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Rakuten cashback</strong></td>
            <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 700;">~$1,000/year</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #f59e0b;">
            <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;"><strong>HYSA interest vs. big bank</strong></td>
            <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 700;">~$200-400/year</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #f59e0b;">
            <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;"><strong>BILT rent points (value)</strong></td>
            <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 700;">~$300-600/year</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0; font-size: 1.125rem;"><strong>Total Annual Value</strong></td>
            <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0; font-size: 1.5rem; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 900;">$3,500+</td>
          </tr>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Layer 1: The Card Stack (~$2,500/year)
      </h2>

      <p>
        Most people use one credit card for everything. Maybe a 1.5% or 2% flat-rate card. That's fine, but you're leaving money on the table.
      </p>

      <p>
        Here's the math: If you spend $3,000/month with a 1.5% card, you earn $540/year. With a strategic 2-3 card stack hitting different bonus categories, that same $3,000/month can earn $900-1,200/year. The difference is $360-660 extra — just for pulling out a different piece of plastic.
      </p>

      <p>
        My 3-card system:
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Card 1: BILT 2.0 + BILT Cash (for rent)</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>What I use it for:</strong> Rent ($2,500/month)
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>What I earn:</strong> 30,000 BILT points per year (1 point per dollar on rent, no fees)
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>Value:</strong> $300-600/year depending on how I redeem (cash value to airline transfers)
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Card 2: Costco Anywhere Visa (for gas + groceries)</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>What I use it for:</strong> All gas, all Costco purchases
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>What I earn:</strong> 4% on gas (up to $7,000/year), 2% on all Costco purchases
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>Value:</strong> ~$600-800/year (gas + Costco shopping + Executive membership reward)
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Card 3: BILT Palladium (for everything else)</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>What I use it for:</strong> Dining, online shopping, miscellaneous
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>What I earn:</strong> 1-3x BILT points depending on category, no annual fee
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
          <strong>Value:</strong> ~$400-600/year
        </p>
      </div>

      <MascotTip type="tip">
        <p>Why 3 cards and not 1? Because no single card offers the best rate in every category. BILT dominates rent. Costco dominates gas. Each card covers what it's best at, and together they optimize my full spending profile.</p>
      </MascotTip>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Layer 2: The Rakuten Stack (~$1,000/year)
      </h2>

      <p>
        This is where most people miss out completely. Rakuten (and portals like it) give you cashback for shopping at stores you were already buying from — and it stacks on top of your credit card rewards.
      </p>

      <p>
        My workflow is simple: Before I buy anything online, I check Rakuten. If the store offers cashback, I click through Rakuten first, then use my credit card as normal.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Real examples from my account:</strong>
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1.5rem 2rem; line-height: 1.8;">
        <li>Lowe's home improvement order: 10% Rakuten + 2% Palladium = 12% total back</li>
        <li>Nike shoes: 8% Rakuten + 3% online bonus = 11% total back</li>
        <li>eBay electronics: 4% Rakuten + 2% card = 6% total back</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Over a year, this adds up to roughly $1,000 in Rakuten cashback alone — on purchases I was making anyway. I didn't change what I bought or where I shopped. I just added one extra click.
      </p>

      <MascotTip type="pick">
        <p>Rakuten pays out quarterly via PayPal or check. I've earned over $5,000 total since I started using it. The browser extension makes it effortless — it pops up automatically when I'm on a cashback-eligible site.</p>
      </MascotTip>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Layer 3: High-Yield Savings Accounts
      </h2>

      <p>
        This one isn't "rewards" in the traditional sense, but it's free money you're leaving on the table if you keep savings in a big bank earning 0.01%.
      </p>

      <p>
        I keep my emergency fund and short-term savings split across three high-yield savings accounts:
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1.5rem 2rem; line-height: 1.8;">
        <li><strong>Robinhood:</strong> Currently 4.5% APY, instant access</li>
        <li><strong>SoFi:</strong> Currently 4.4% APY, frequent bonuses</li>
        <li><strong>Wealthfront:</strong> Currently 4.5% APY, clean interface</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Why three? Rate shopping, bonus capture, and FDIC diversification. Rates change constantly, and having accounts at multiple platforms means I can shift money to whoever's offering the best rate or sign-up bonus.
      </p>

      <p>
        On $10,000 in savings, 4.5% APY = $450/year. At a big bank earning 0.01%? You'd get $1. The difference is $449/year in free money just for moving your cash to a better account.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Layer 4: Sign-Up Bonuses (Year 1 Boost)
      </h2>

      <p>
        In your first year of optimizing, sign-up bonuses can add another $500-1,000+ on top of your ongoing rewards.
      </p>

      <p>
        My approach: Only go for bonuses on cards I'll actually use long-term. I don't churn cards or hit minimum spends on stuff I don't need. If I was already planning to get a card for its ongoing rewards, the sign-up bonus is a nice accelerator.
      </p>

      <p>
        Examples:
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1.5rem 2rem; line-height: 1.8;">
        <li>Amex Blue Cash Everyday: $200 after $2,000 spend in 6 months (easy to hit)</li>
        <li>Chase Freedom Unlimited: $300 after $500 spend in 3 months (trivial)</li>
        <li>Amazon Prime Rewards: $200 gift card after first purchase (instant)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Once you have your core stack, these bonuses fade into the background. But in year one, they're a meaningful boost.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Putting It All Together
      </h2>

      <p>
        Here's the annual breakdown for my actual spending:
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <table style="width: 100%; font-size: 0.9375rem; line-height: 1.8;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-border);">
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 700;">Source</th>
              <th style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 700;">Annual Value</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;">BILT rent points (30K points)</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0;">$300-600</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;">Costco card (gas + groceries)</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0;">$600-800</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;">BILT Palladium (everything else)</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0;">$400-600</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;">Rakuten cashback</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0;">$1,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;">HYSA interest (vs. 0.01% big bank)</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0;">$200-400</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 0.75rem 0;">Sign-up bonuses (year 1)</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 0.75rem 0;">$500-1,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.125rem; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
              <td style="padding: 1rem 0;">Total Annual Value</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem 0; color: var(--color-success); font-size: 1.5rem;">$3,500+</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>
        This isn't about being a credit card nerd or spending hours optimizing. It's simple math:
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1.5rem 2rem; line-height: 1.8;">
        <li>Use the right card for each spending category</li>
        <li>Click through Rakuten before online purchases</li>
        <li>Keep savings in accounts that actually pay interest</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Total time investment per month: ~10 minutes. Total annual value: ~$3,500.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Build Your Own Stack
      </h2>

      <p>
        My card stack works for my spending. Yours will be different. If you don't pay rent, BILT isn't useful. If you don't shop at Costco, the Costco card isn't optimal. If you spend more on dining than I do, maybe Amex Gold makes sense.
      </p>

      <p>
        The principle stays the same: identify your top 3-4 spending categories, find the best card for each, and stack them together.
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-secondary-bg); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-secondary); padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; border-radius: var(--radius-md);">
        <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-secondary-dark); margin: 0;">
          Use the <a href="/find-cards" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline;">Card Stack Builder</a> to calculate your optimal combination based on your actual spending.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Frequently Asked Questions
      </h2>

      <FAQSection faqs={[
        {
          question: "How much time does this actually take per month?",
          answer: "About 10 minutes total. Pulling out the right card becomes automatic after the first month. Rakuten takes one extra click per online purchase. Checking HYSA rates takes 5 minutes once a quarter. This isn't a part-time job — it's a few tiny habits that compound to thousands per year."
        },
        {
          question: "Will opening multiple cards hurt my credit score?",
          answer: "Short-term: each new card application causes a small temporary dip (usually 5-10 points). Long-term: having more available credit and a longer average account age improves your score. I've opened 5+ cards over the past 3 years and my score is higher now than when I started. Just don't open them all at once."
        },
        {
          question: "What if I don't pay rent? Can I still use this system?",
          answer: "Absolutely. BILT is only valuable if you pay rent. If you own or live rent-free, skip it and focus on your actual top spending categories. Use the Card Stack Builder to find your optimal combination — it'll recommend different cards based on what you actually spend money on."
        },
        {
          question: "Do I need good credit to get approved for these cards?",
          answer: "For the premium cards (Amex Gold, etc.), yes — you'll typically need a credit score of 700+. But cards like Discover it, Capital One SavorOne, and even some BILT cards have lower barriers. Start with what you can get approved for, use them responsibly, and upgrade as your credit improves."
        },
        {
          question: "Is $3,500/year realistic for everyone?",
          answer: "My number is based on my specific spending: $2,500/month rent, regular Costco trips, and consistent online shopping. If you spend less, your total will be lower. If you spend more (especially on high-reward categories like dining or travel), your total could be higher. The principle works at any spending level — you're just optimizing whatever you're already spending."
        }
      ]} />

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Related Guides
      </h2>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 2rem 0; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/strategies/credit-card-stacking" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">Credit Card Stacking: How to Maximize Rewards with 2-3 Cards</a>
        </li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/strategies/how-to-pay-rent-with-credit-card" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">How to Pay Rent with a Credit Card and Earn Points</a>
        </li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/find-cards" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">Card Stack Builder Tool</a>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <EmailCapture
        variant="article-end"
        headline="Want the full tracking spreadsheet?"
        description="Get the same Google Sheets template I use to track all my rewards and calculate my annual total."
        buttonText="Send me the spreadsheet"
      />

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
